We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the OIC – Municipal Accountant to

(a) cause the immediate liquidation of the cash advances granted to LGU officials/employees;


(b) ensure that the liquidation reports are submitted within the prescribed period to the Office of the COA Auditor for review, together with all the necessary documents attached therein, such as the official receipts, certificate of seminar/trainings completed, etc.;

(c) exert effort in locating documents on cash advances to properly establish the accountability of the responsible accountable officers; and

(d) refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers with outstanding account.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the

(a) OIC – Municipal Treasurer and OIC – Municipal Accountant to 

(i) review and settle the difference of the cashbook and general ledger balances of the Advances for Operating Expenses account; and 

(ii) strictly observe Section 6.3 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

(b) OIC – Municipal Accountant to 

(i) record the reconciling items identified; 

(ii); refrain from granting additional cash advances without reporting and settlement of the previous cash advance; 


(iii) ensure that the documentary  requirements prescribed in COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-001 dated February 10, 1997 and June 14, 2012, respectively, on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances are properly complied with; and 

(iv) effect the payment of goods and services directly to the supplier except in cases where the needed items are extremely necessary and urgent in which case reimbursement may be allowed; and

(c) OIC – Municipal Treasurer to liquidate her cash advance within the prescribed period or as soon as the purpose for which it is given has been served.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the

(a) Inventory Committee and designated GSO to 

(i) conduct physical inventory of all PPE of the Municipality on or before January 31 of each year, conclude said inventory count for CY 2022 and immediately submit the related reports to the Office of the Auditor; 



(ii) reconcile the resultant inventory reports with the Accounting records;

(b) OIC -Municipal Accountant and GSO to 

(i) maintain complete PPE records such as PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards for the proper control and monitoring of the agency property and equipment; 



(ii) facilitate the renewal of registrations and insurance coverage of Motor Vehicles; and 

(iii) consider the one-time cleaning of PPE account balances to improve the reliability of the PPE accounts;



(c) OIC - Municipal Accountant to

(i) reconstruct the records of Registry of Public Infrastructure to identify the infrastructure projects for transfer to the appropriate asset accounts; and

(ii)  secure from the DPWH Nueva Ecija 2nd DEO the Certificate of Acceptance and other lacking documents related to the transferred properties.

We recommended and the LCE together with the OIC – Municipal HRM Officer agreed to

(i) formulate and issue approved policy guidelines on the hiring of job order promulgating the standards for uniform application in consideration of the provisions of CSC Resolution No. 020790 dated June 5, 2002; 

ensure compliance with Section 1 of PD No. 143 and accord weekly rest days for job orders; 

provide approved standard daily wage rate to job orders performing the same function and having the same designation; and

(b) require the OIC – Municipal HRM Officer and OIC – Municipal Accountant to ensure compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012 – 001 dated June 14, 2012 on the submission of required supporting documents before processing the payment of wages of job orders.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the

(a) LDRRM Officer and the OIC – Municipal Accountant to comply with the planning and reporting requirements for LDRRMF as provided for under NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 and COA Circular No. 2012-002;

(b) effect the corrections in the reporting of LDRRMF and observe procedures in the preparation of the reports;

(c) OIC – Municipal Treasurer to

(i) transfer the unutilized QRF and the DRRMF – MOOE for CY 2022 amounting to ₱621,159.76 to the account Trust Liability – DRRM in the Trust Fund books;

(ii) revert back to the general fund the unutilized DRRMF – Capital Outlay amounting to ₱1,592,808.94 which was erroneously transferred to the Trust Liability – DRRM in the Trust Fund books; and

(iii)  remit the excess NDRRMF amounting to ₱5,209,066.49 to the Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the 
(a) Municipal Accountant to 

(i) recognize the procurement of relief goods, medicines and office supplies for stock, distribution and consumption as Inventory under the perpetual inventory method; 

(ii) maintain Supplies Ledger Card for each commodity/stock; 

(iii) compute the inventory cost monthly using the moving average method; and (iv) recognize in the books the issuance of inventory based on the submitted Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI); and 
(b) General Services Officer to 

(i) maintain Stock Cards for supplies in their custody to account for the receipt and disposition of the same; 

(ii) consolidate monthly the Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) for supplies and materials using the RSMI; and 

(iii) submit the RSMI together with the original copy of the RIS to the Municipal Accountant.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 
(a) instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the documents required for further review/evaluation of the claims; 
(b) explain/justify why the rate per day used as basis in the computation were not uniform; 
(c) re-compute the COVID-19 Hazard Pay received by each personnel based on the actual number of days an employee physically reported for work during the ECQ; and 
(d) submit copy of DTRs of the employees without DTRs.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to 
(a) cause the immediate liquidation of the cash advances granted to LGU officials/employees; 
(b) ensure that the liquidation reports are submitted to the Office of the COA Auditor for review, together with all the necessary documents attached therein, such as the official receipts, certificate of seminar/trainings completed, etc.; (c) exert effort in locating documents on cash advances to properly establish the responsible accountable officer; 
(d) refrain from granting additional cash advances without first liquidating the previous cash advance; and 
(e) reconcile the difference of the GL and SL balances of the Due from Officers and Employees account and recognize the necessary adjustment in the account.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to –
reconstitute an Inventory Committee to include each Department Head to facilitate inventory-taking by Office of all the property, plant and equipment of the Municipality;
require the Acting General Services Officer (GSO) to (i) maintain Property Cards starting with the current and recent years’ acquisitions and aim for a yearly increase of coverage until all PPE items are covered; (ii) reconcile inventory results with property records and those maintained at the Accounting Office and isolate items not reconciled for easy reference in succeeding inventory-taking; and (iii) aim to reduce the number and amount of unreconciled PPE account balances;
require the Municipal Accountant to (i) compute and take - up the depreciation expenses of the current year, update the related accumulated depreciation accounts as well as record adjustments in the government equity account for prior years’ depreciation expense which were not previously recorded; and (ii) determine the projects transferred to Registry of Public Infrastructure for 100% recognition in the appropriate asset accounts; and
require the Inventory Committee to undertake complete physical inventory of all property of the municipality, prepare complete and detailed corresponding report thereon and reconcile the result with the accounting records.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Assessor, ICO – Municipal Treasurer and General Services Officer to:
coordinate with each other and reconcile their records to ascertain the correctness of the Land account balance;
appropriate funds and facilitate the registration in the name of the Municipal Government the parcel of lots which were not yet covered by TCT to preclude third party claims over said properties;
work-out the cancellation of encumbrance carried on TCT No. NT – 292093;
exert effort to locate the owners copy of TCT No. NT – 83018 and TCT No. NT – 110866 or facilitate reconstitution of these land titles; and

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the –
Members of the Local Finance Committee continue to ensure that the required appropriations for LDRRMF is met;
LDRRM Officer to (i) ensure the optimal utilization of the LDRRMF for projects/activities for each thematic area provided under Paragraphs 5.1 to 5.5 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC 2013 – 1; and (ii) coordinate with the OIC – Municipal Engineer and the Bids and Awards Committee for the proper planning, implementation and monitoring of all construction/infrastructure projects at the most feasible time;
ICO – Municipal Treasurer to transfer the unexpended QRF and MF – MOOE to the TF bank account; and
Municipal Accountant to maintain a subsidiary ledger for the transfer of agency’s unutilized DRRMF to the special trust fund by year of transfer.

We recommended and the Management agreed to –
exercise prudence in the utilization of resources intended for meals and snacks during meetings and other activities of the Municipality;
observe the limitations for such expenditures as prescribed in the budget ordinance;
diligently and judiciously plan all official activities that demand meals and snacks taking into considerations the frequency, the number of participants, and undertake all available austerity measures to minimize expenses related thereto; and
submit necessary documents such as attendance sheet, programme, pictures to prove the validity of the transactions.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to –
instruct the Project Development Officer to expedite the implementation of projects for the site development and construction of the MMRF in Brgy. Niyugan;
require every barangay to establish their own BMRF subject to the guidelines and criteria set pursuant to RA 9003;
strictly enforce the sanctions to violators of the rules and regulations on ecological solid waste management.

We reiterated our recommendation and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to:

send collection letters to the recipients of Poverty Alleviation Programs with uncollected receivable balance in the books;

strictly monitor the uncollected balances of receivable accounts to facilitate its timely collection;

exert all possible means to locate the necessary records and documents that would lead to the possible recovery of the amount due to the government; and

re-assess the chances of recoverability of receivables, and if warranted,  consider filing a request to write-off the accounts that have been dormant for more than ten years with the Commission on Audit pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005,  dated December 19, 2016.

